        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our goals are (i) to get higher resolution data of the cores and (ii) to get deeper images to get access
to the lower mass cluster members. We have conducted simulations in CASA 4.1 (tasks simobserve and
simanalyze), with a synthetic image which represents the observed I(N) structure (Fig. 1a), except that we
split up the main cores into components and added some lower mass members. The simulations show that
goals (i) and (ii) are somewhat orthogonal to each other, since very high resolution data (needed for (i))
have a lower dynamic range due to the fact that more emission is resolved out which results in artifacts
and thus prevent reaching goal (ii). We conclude that a combination of the configuration C34-7 and C34-3
provide the best results to achieve both goals. A simulated observation of the other source I leads to the
same conclusion and image fidelity as for source I(N). Because I &amp; I(N) are extended up to 10 arcsec, the
ACA is needed to recover the flux on the largest scales. Both sources lie near together with a sky separation
of 2 arcmin and can be observed in a track-sharing mode. The estimated total time of 3.2h with the two
12m-arrays splits up in 2.2 h for band 7 and 1 h for band 6.
Frequency and Correlator setup: The spectral setup in band 7 ranges in the LSB from 342-346 GHz
and in the USB from 354-358 GHz. In the USB, one baseband is centered at the center frequency of HCN
and the other baseband is set in continuum mode. In the LSB, one baseband covers transitions of CO,
H13CN and HC15N, and the other baseband is set in continuum mode as well. The typical linewidth is
4 km/s in I &amp; I(N), and we choose a velocity resolution of 0.4 km/s to sample the spectral line profiles.
As we want to cover a broad bandwidth, we chose single polarization to get a large number of spectral
channels. Both sources contain line rich hot cores, therefore both continuum basebands will be used for the
continuum imaging (TDM mode) with at least 4 GHz bandwidth. The spectral setup in band 6 ranges in
the LSB from 226-230 GHz and in the USB from 241-245.5 GHz. In the USB, one baseband is centered at
the center frequency of CS and the other baseband contains CS-33 and several methanol transitions. In the
LSB, both basebands will be used for the continuum imaging (TDM mode).
Requested sensitivity: We detect 5 continuum sources with peak fluxes in the range of 1.9 to 0.4 Jy/beam
at 350 GHz in I(N). Since our resolution is higher and we expect some sources to be resolved, our peak
fluxes will be actually lower, by a factor of a few. The simulated image (Fig. 1b) results in peak fluxes of
100 mJy/beam for I(N)-SMA1 and 4 mJy/beam for the faintest fragments. Thus, to have a sufficient S/N
ratio, our requested sensitivity is 0.2 mJy/beam in the continuum baseband of 4.0 GHz in band 6 and 7,
which corresponds to a mass sensitivity of a fraction of a solar mass. At the finest velocity resolution in band
7, the sensitivity will be 15 mJy/beam and sufficient to detect the weakest desired transition of HC15N.
As already discussed, the pointings towards the brightest sources I-SMA1 and I(N)-SMA1 will be dynamic
range limited. The rms is about 1 mJy/beam in the combined simulated image of all 3 arrays (Fig. 1b) and
0.6 mJy/beam in a simulated observation in the configuration C34-7, which is higher than the theoretical
sensitivity of 0.2 mJy/beam from the sensitivity calculator, but still low enough to detect the faintest cores
and achieve the science goal.
Imaging requirements: We go for the highest resolution and request for high fidelity quality images. As
all cores cannot be covered with a single pointing, a mosaic (Nyquist-sampled) of 7 pointings will be used
for both sources in band 7 and 3 pointings in band 6. We checked the outcome with a simulation of the
observations. The C34-7 array configuration in combination with the C34-3 configuration gives good results,
and the ACA recovers the large scale flux in the central region, see Fig. 1b.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
